metadata.name: Back to Eden [four seasons] #26
metadata.description:
I, who erewhile the happy Garden sung 
By one man’s disobedience lost, now sing 
Recovered Paradise to all mankind, 
By one man’s firm obedience fully tried
Through all temptation, and the Tempter foiled 
In all his wiles, defeated and repulsed, 
And Eden raised in the waste wilderness.

[John Milton - Paradise regained (1671)]

This project is the NFT reworking of a work of a few years ago in which I conceived a landscape evolving its parameters from one season to another.
4 seasons = 4 features.
The parameters concern the shapes of the trunks, branches, leaves, their colors and the colors of the background.

metadata.name: Shine On You Crazy Diamond #17
metadata.description:
This artwork is an attempt to depict lights seen through textured and coloured glass windows. It's coded entirely in p5.js and is made of only rectangles, thousands of them.

Best viewed on a screen bigger than a mobile phone, while listening to this track called ‘Shine On You Crazy Diamond Parts I-V' by Pink Floyd: https://open.spotify.com/track/6pnwfWyaWjQiHCKTiZLItr

Artwork loads at 1000px by 1000px resolution by default. Press ‘2’,’4’ or ‘8’ to load as 2000px by 2000px, 4000px by 4000px or 8000px by 8000px respectively.
Press 's' at any time to download the rendered resolution.

Credits:
- Landed on this technique when experimenting with ideas in this essay by Tyler Hobbs: https://tylerxhobbs.com/essays/2015/creating-soft-textures-generatively
- Although my logic to create grids is slightly different, this blog by Gorilla Sun was a good starting point & guide: https://gorillasun.de/blog/an-algorithm-for-irregular-grids
- The name of the artwork is a tribute to my favourite band

metadata.name: Redo #46
metadata.description:
Redo" is abstract art made with 100% p5.js code and mathematics in the form of a Triptych.
Using a flow filed with always the same noise seed, the form is presented in three time periods through three shapes.


Created with 100% p5.js code and math.

Hi-res. options:

- press 'i' to save .png with resolution = 1000px x 1000px
- press 't' to save .png with resolution = 2000px x 2000px
- press 's' to save .png with resolution = 6000px x 6000px

Created using p5js.

@Mutart, August, 2022.

metadata.name: Puzzles of the mind #103
metadata.description:
This is abstract art based on mathematical structure.
The puzzle of your mind seems broken and rearranged.

Mode has 2 variations.
 - Normal
 - Black
Color has 3 variations.
 - 常磐-tokiwa- (Green)
 - 真朱-shinshu- (Red)
 - 紺碧-konpeki- (Blue)
Color Level has 2 variations.
 - High
 - Low
Square Size has 3 variations.
 - Small
 - Middle
 - Large

Tokiwa is a Japanese word meaning always the same. It's green like the color of evergreen leaves.

Shinshu is a Japanese word that refers to a dull red color like vermilion. It means vermilion in its natural state with nothing mixed in.

Konpeki is a Japanese word that describes a deep blue, very close to azure. It's like a clear sky with summer sunshine.

Controls (in live view):
 - Press [f] to switch full screen on and off
 - Press [s] to download a PNG file with windowsize
 - Press [l] to download a PNG file with large size 4800 pixel (wait a minutes)

Create with p5.js
License: CC BY-NC-SA 4.0

metadata.name: Kinetograms #254
metadata.description:
Each Kinetogram traces the movement of a number of simple shapes constrained within a single cell or a grid of cells. Forces are applied to the shapes in the form of attraction, gravity or shaking.

Some Kinetograms are partially or completely reflected, vertically or horizontally, some with chromatic replacement.

The aspect ratio is 3:4. The palettes are predominantly based on found textile patterns.

Press 's' to save a png image. Press 'e' to redraw and export a 4K png image. Note that drawing and physical simulation takes some time.

For interactive use, press 't' to tilt the board and 'c' to clear the board.

Written in p5.js with 2D physical simulation using Matter.js. Developed in and optimized for Chrome.
